{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f0cd8613-3409-45eb-af3b-857ad4ae21a7","content":"Yes, both approaches are correct for .NET MAUI on .NET 10.\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This is a valid iOS platform-specific that adjusts the page's padding to avoid the notch/Dynamic Island and home indicator. In your XAML, you need the namespace:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\nThen apply it:\n```xml\n<ContentPage ... ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This is also correct. It lets a specific view (like a Grid with a background image) extend *beyond* the safe area to fill the full screen, even when the page uses safe area padding. This gives you the best of both worlds: content stays in the safe zone, but your background bleeds edge-to-edge.\n\n```xml\n<Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</Grid>\n```\n\nBoth APIs remain available and are the recommended approach in .NET 10.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4421e297-2c4e-4f5f-88df-fb7c46f77c3d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - a property on Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about these APIs in .NET MAUI, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI (which evolved from Xamarin.Forms), the safe area handling changed:\n\n1. **`ios:Page.UseSafeArea`** - In Xamarin.Forms, this was `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` using the platform-specific namespace. In .NET MAUI, this was carried forward but the approach has evolved. The correct way in .NET MAUI is to use `Page.UseSafeArea` as a platform-specific API via `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific`.\n\n\n2. **`IgnoreSafeArea`** - Views in .NET MAUI have an `IgnoreSafeArea` property that allows them to extend beyond the safe area boundaries. I need to be careful about the .NET 10 timeline though—since it's expected in November 2026, I should focus on what's currently stable in .NET MAUI rather than speculating about preview features.\n\nThe key distinction is that `Page.UseSafeArea` is an iOS platform-specific property that automatically adjusts padding to account for notches and home indicators, while `IgnoreSafeArea` on individual views lets them break out of those constraints when needed. Both approaches should remain valid in .NET 10 since they're core to how MAUI handles safe areas across platforms.","outputTokens":1036},"id":"7fd484d2-4b9c-4701-b3ab-e16b778e0921","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:54:58.187Z","parentId":"657bdbad-9372-403f-aba5-3f045a6d764a"}
